# .cursorrules — Frontend Website

## Design Approach
Before writing any frontend code, apply the frontend-design skill below. Every session, no exceptions.

Commit to a bold, intentional aesthetic direction before touching code:
- Pick an extreme tone: brutally minimal, maximalist, retro-futuristic, editorial, brutalist, etc.
- Choose distinctive fonts — never Inter, Roboto, Arial, or system fonts. Pair a display/serif with a clean sans.
- Commit to a custom color palette. Never use default Tailwind colors (indigo-500, blue-600, etc.).
- Make it unforgettable. One clear conceptual direction, executed with precision.

## Reference Images
- If a reference image is provided: match layout, spacing, typography, and color exactly. Use placeholder content (https://placehold.co/ for images). Do not improve or add to the design.
- If no reference image: design from scratch with high craft using the guardrails below.

## Output Defaults
- Single index.html file, all styles inline, unless told otherwise
- Tailwind CSS via CDN: <script src="https://cdn.tailwindcss.com"></script>
- Placeholder images: https://placehold.co/WIDTHxHEIGHT
- Mobile-first responsive

## Brand Assets
- Always check the brand_assets/ folder before designing.
- If a logo exists, use it. If a color palette is defined, use those exact values — do not invent brand colors.
- Never use placeholders where real assets are available.

## Anti-Generic Guardrails
- Colors: Never use default Tailwind palette. Pick a custom brand color and derive a palette from it.
- Shadows: No flat shadow-md. Use layered, color-tinted shadows with low opacity.
- Typography: Never use the same font for headings and body. Apply tight tracking (-0.03em) on large headings, generous line-height (1.7) on body.
- Gradients: Layer multiple radial gradients. Add grain/texture via SVG noise filter for depth.
- Animations: Only animate transform and opacity. Never transition-all. Use spring-style easing.
- Interactive states: Every clickable element needs hover, focus-visible, and active states. No exceptions.
- Images: Add a gradient overlay (bg-gradient-to-t from-black/60) and a color treatment layer with mix-blend-multiply.
- Spacing: Use intentional, consistent spacing tokens — not random Tailwind steps.
- Depth: Surfaces should have a layering system (base → elevated → floating). Not all at the same z-plane.

## Hard Rules
- Do not add sections, features, or content not in the reference
- Do not "improve" a reference design — match it
- Do not use transition-all
- Do not use default Tailwind blue/indigo as primary color

## Frontend Design Skill
You are building distinctive, production-grade frontend interfaces that avoid generic AI aesthetics.

Design Thinking — before coding:
- Understand the purpose: what problem does this solve, who uses it?
- Pick an extreme tone and commit fully to it
- Identify what makes this design unforgettable

Typography:
- Avoid Inter, Roboto, Arial, Space Grotesk, and system fonts
- Pair a distinctive display font with a refined body font
- Use Google Fonts or similar

Color & Theme:
- Use CSS variables for all colors
- Dominant colors with sharp accents outperform timid, evenly-distributed palettes
- Commit to a cohesive aesthetic

Motion:
- Only animate transform and opacity
- Staggered reveals on load create more delight than scattered micro-interactions
- Use scroll-triggering and hover states that surprise

Spatial Composition:
- Unexpected layouts — asymmetry, overlap, diagonal flow, grid-breaking elements
- Generous negative space OR controlled density — pick one

Backgrounds & Visual Details:
- Create atmosphere: gradient meshes, noise textures, geometric patterns, layered transparencies
- Dramatic shadows, decorative borders, grain overlays

Never use:
- Purple gradients on white backgrounds (overused)
- Predictable, cookie-cutter component patterns
- The same layout structure across different projects

Vary between light and dark themes, different fonts, different aesthetics per project.
